Introduction

The full list of steps are listed here in the Release Check list for Azure SDK for .NET guide.

Steps

From your main up-to-date branch of the azure-sdk-for-net run the following command: 
.\eng\common\scripts\Prepare-Release.ps1 -PackageName Azure.AI.OpenAI -ServiceDirectory openai -ReleaseDate 2/8/2023
You will be prompted about the name of the release. The default is generally always good, as upon completing the release there will be an auto complete PR opened updating the value for the next. In this case: 
Input the new version, or press Enter to use use current project version '1.0.0-beta.2':

You will be asked to install azure-cli if you don't have it installed. Follow the link suggestion, install and reopen your terminal and re-run the command. Accepting the name for the release will then prompt you to login with your work account for the azure-cli

The script will then link an issue that will be automatically created for the release. Open it.

Find your commit for the release in the pipeline list found in Pipelines - Runs for net - openai (azure.com)

You will need access (manager approved) to the group of approvers. It can be requested from this link

You will be prompted to select a branch and supply a commit. Simply leaving the branch to "main" (provided that all your changes are in there) and the commit blank, will use HEAD and continue on with the deployment.

Development

Per language in depth guides

.NET Java

Approach overview

This space moves fast and we need to be able to react quickly to new features, new SDK language requirements, new Azure feature integrations, and new "things we don't even know about yet."

To facilitate that, we've partnered with Azure DevDiv to use their code generation ecosystem, built around a language and related tools called typespec (formerly cadl), as the basis for how AOAI SDK code is produced.

https://microsoft.github.io/typespec/

The idea here is: - Together with the service teams, REST contracts are authored as typespec files - Language-specific SDKs ingest emitted code from these typespec sources as a "generated" base - Those SDKs can then add custom code when needed to facilitate specialized or language-specific functionality -- or to tailor the code generation step itself

As an elaboration of that last part, code generation has a bidirectional, mutually-informative relationship with custom code: adding fields or methods to custom code (e.g. with custom visibility or implementation) will suppress/replace code generation, meaning language-specific SDKs still have a great deal of freedom.

And the goals of that? - Less time is spent writing and maintaining non-scenario-focused, boilerplate code around things like authentication, basic network I/O, etc. - We get the latest and greatest integration with Azure.Core "for free" as code gen is updated - We can respond to changes much more quickly since code generation can do most (or all!) of the work for us

But, it's important to keep in mind: - We should never author API surfaces a certain way "because that's what code generation does." Codegen may give us a solid basis derived from guidelines and best practices, but we ultimately must still do what we think is correct for customers! - If/when we discover gaps or mismatches or we just get blocked, it's OK for us to implement new things in their intended forms as custom code to begin with; the idea is for tooling and process to help and accelerate us, not slow us down or contrain us

That said, the more custom code we adopt the slower we can move and the more we maintain, so every effort should be made to translate custom code to codegen ASAP where applicable and reasonable

Repos of interest

The typespec repository is what define what code generation will output for a new language SDK:

Azure Rest API Spec. In this repository we are particularly interested in two paths:

specification/cognitiveservices/OpenAI.Inference: contains the typespec specification for this service.

specification/cognitiveservices/data-plane/AzureOpenAI: contains the swagger JSON definition for the SDK service. As of the writing of this document we are only concerned with the inference where you will find the stable and preview folders containing the corresponding release version of the channel they are named after.

Repositories for each supported languages (list could be outdated)

Azure SDK for .NET. In this repository we are interested in a couple of paths too:

sdk/openai/ contains the code for the SDK. Specifically within Azure.AI.OpenAI you will find the source code and tests.

eng/scripts contains PowerShell scripts that you will have to generally run whenever you open a PR.

Azure SDK for Java

At the time of this writing, the SDK is not merged into main yet. You can find the current development under this branch

If you need to iterate quickly on TypeSpec changes and don't mind some additional manual steps, you can follow these instructions instead:

CAUTION: While using this method: Any changes you make in the TempTypeSpecFiles\OpenAI.Inference subfolder are ignored by source control Running dotnet build /t:GenerateCommand will overwrite your changes. You should only use the tsp compile ... command to regenerate until you have copied your changes into your sparse-spec TypeSpec repo clone (sparse-spec\Azure.AI.OpenAI) From the command line, re-generate the auto generated C# code using the following: dotnet build /t:GenerateCode /p:SaveInputs=true Please note the additional /p:SaveInputs=True. This will instruct the generation scripts to keep the temporary folders and files it uses The temporary files can be found in the sdk\openai\Azure.AI.OpenAI\TempTypeSpecFiles\OpenAI.Inference subfolder Please note the tsp compile command that is echoed during the build and copy and save that (without the npx). In my case the command was tsp compile C:\azure-sdk-for-net\sdk\openai\Azure.AI.OpenAI\TempTypeSpecFiles\OpenAI.Inference\main.tsp --emit @azure-tools/typespec-csharp --option @azure-tools/typespec-csharp.emitter-output-dir=C:\azure-sdk-for-net\sdk\openai\Azure.AI.OpenAI\src Open up the following folder in VSCode: sdk\openai\Azure.AI.OpenAI\TempTypeSpecFiles\OpenAI.Inference Make the changes you need to the Typespec files To re-generate the C# code, in your .Net repo copy and paste the command you saved earlier (tsp compile ...) If you see warnings/errors about a mismatched tsp version, try navigating to the advised folder (e.g. TempTypeSpecFiles\OpenAI.Inference) and try again Once you're happy with how the local, temp TypeSpec change are behaving, move them into your sparse-spec TypeSpec repo clone (sparse-spec\Azure.AI.OpenAI) Committing the changes Once you're happy with the way your TypeSpec changes are behaving, commit them to your fork/topic branch in the TypeSpec sparse repo clone Create and merge a PR of your changes into the TypeSpec (Azure/azure-rest-api-specs) repo Note: This PR process into the TypeSpec repo must be completed before proceeding to the next steps Go back to your .Net repo and update the commit referenced in sdk\openai\Azure.AI.OpenAI\tsp-location.yaml to match the commit you just made to TypeSpec repo Regenerate and rebuild the C# code using the full dotnet build /t:GenerateCode,GenerateTests,Build /p:UpdateSourceOnBuild=true flow to pick up your changes You can manually update the snippets, and API exports using PowerShell core (pwsh) (NOT the built in Windows Powershell): ```powershell ......\eng\scripts\Export-API.ps1 -ServiceDirectory openai ......\eng\scripts\Update-Snippets.ps1 -ServiceDirectory openai ","title":"Dev notes","url":null,"filepath":"dev_docs\dotnet.md","chunk_id":"0"},{"content":"

Azure OpenAI

Important This guide was written while typespec was still called cadl. These terms should be understood as interchangable throughout this doc.

This is the internal documentation for developers wanting a guide to on-board themselves in the setup, development and deployment process of the Azure OpenAI SDKs.

The .NET SDK can be found in nuget

If you need more detailed help or invitation to any of the meetings or channels touched on this documentation get in contact with either:

Travis Wilson Glenn Harper Jose Alvarez Brandon Miller (brandom@microsoft.com)

Index of links

Concepts and quick starts Development Testing approach Deployment process

Appendix: Development Process

We have two weekly meetings:

Weekly Azure AI SDK sync@10:00 or 16:30 every Tuesday. This meeting has a PM focus and generally where many teams intersect and provide non-technical updates on all things AI. This meeting is facilitated by Arun Chandrasekhar.

OpenAI Cadl Sync@9:00 every Wednesday. The focus of this meeting is to provide guidance on the usage of cadl for the SDK and service description. This meeting is technical. You can find the meeting logs are available in the file history of the channel. The meeting is facilitated by Jose Alvarez.

We used to have a sync meeting with the team leads from the Carbon team as well. Currently, there is personal involvement of management in the effort therefore this meeting was abandoned.

Currently we are tracking Sorento work items in ADO here (Requires you to be tented to access)

(May be out of date) You can search in ADO and filter by Skyman\Carbon\OpenAI work area. Generally, we create epics which are parents of user stories which are themselves parents of concrete actionable work items.
